text: I'm John Harwood with the New York Times
in CNBC rank-and-file democrats are out
of the picture in the 2008 presidential
race until Pennsylvania's primary next
month so party leaders have taken some
of the most important action behind
closed doors it's the attempt to
negotiate a solution to the mess
involving Michigan and Florida and
whether their delegates will have a role
in the Clinton Obama fight The
Situation's unprecedented because it
combines large states a live nomination
battle and the electoral version of
instant replay when the DNC stripped
Michigan in Florida of Delegates last
year for holding primaries too early no
one anticipated a race extending long
enough that the exclusion mattered but
in this very close race it plainly does
matter and so there's pressure for new
contests especially from the Clinton
campaign which needs more victories to
overtake Obama but the cost and
complication of new contests which under
party rules must take place by June 10th
represent a challenge for even the most
experienced Democrats one clue to the
final resolution may lie in the two
states divergent political cultures
Michigan once relied on party finance
caucuses rather than state finance
primaries that's made it easier for
Democrats there to devise a plan for a
party finance do-over primary state
legislature may vote on that this week
Florida Democrats lacking that tradition
have fallen into stalemate instead party
leaders are discussing plans to seat
delegates under a negotiated formula one
option seating delegates in proportion
to the taint of January 29th vote but
giving each delegate only one half vote
that would slice mrs. Clinton's edge to
19 delegates from 38 proponents cite two
virtues of this plan Republicans
couldn't attack Democrats for shutting
Florida because Republicans themselves
have already taken away half of
Florida's convention delegates the
second virtue it would save the fifteen
million dollar cost of a new primary but
of course with stakes this large the
rival campaigns themselves will have to
sign off on any negotiated settlement as
veteran Democratic strategist tad Devine
Toby it will be solved by Obama and
Clinton and maybe even at that level
